<subSubSection id="C3136559FFCAFFCBFF0DFEB4E51CFEB2" pageId="15" pageNumber="422" type="breeding">
<paragraph id="8BB636D2FFCAFFCBFF0DFEB4E51CFEB2" blockId="15.[197,1399,259,842]" pageId="15" pageNumber="422">
<emphasis id="B97DEAC0FFCAFFCBFF0DFEB4E771FEDD" bold="true" box="[198,332,259,292]" pageId="15" pageNumber="422">Breeding.</emphasis>
The rutting call begins as a roar but ends in a Wapiti-like bugle. The calving season of the Hangul peaks in July-August.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3136559FFCAFFCBFF0DFEE5E2DFFE38" pageId="15" pageNumber="422" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8BB636D2FFCAFFCBFF0DFEE5E2DFFE38" blockId="15.[197,1399,259,842]" pageId="15" pageNumber="422">
<emphasis id="B97DEAC0FFCAFFCBFF0DFEE5E5B1FE8A" bold="true" box="[198,908,338,371]" pageId="15" pageNumber="422">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
They are saltatorial, able to move with agility on steep slopes in scrub vegetation. They are gregarious, with large family groups. The rare Shou has been seen recently in herds of up to 55 animals.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3136559FFCAFFCBFF0DFE7FE7A2FD02" pageId="15" pageNumber="422" type="conservation">
<paragraph id="8BB636D2FFCAFFCBFF0DFE7FE7A2FD02" blockId="15.[197,1399,259,842]" pageId="15" pageNumber="422">
<emphasis id="B97DEAC0FFCAFFCBFF0DFE7FE418FE10" bold="true" box="[198,549,456,489]" pageId="15" pageNumber="422">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Hangul CITES Appendix I. Considered a subspecies of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C094D51FFCAFFCBFF02FE58E773FDE9" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[201,334,495,528]" class="Mammalia" family="Cervidae" genus="Cervus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Artiodactyla" pageId="15" pageNumber="422" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="elaphus">C. elaphus</taxonomicName>
complex by IUCN and thus not evaluated on The IUCN Red Lust. It is a very rare species, possibly threatened, the Hangul declined from 2000 animals in 1947 to less than 200 animals in the early 1970s, then increased to 1000 by 1989, but dropped again to 150-200 in the last decade. The Shou was considered extinct and rediscovered in a few localities of south-east 
<collectingRegion id="49CDF830FFCAFFCBFD02FD3BE529FD54" box="[713,788,652,685]" country="China" name="Xizang" pageId="15" pageNumber="422">Tibet</collectingRegion>
(
<collectingRegion id="49CDF830FFCAFFCBFCE1FD3BE5B3FD54" box="[810,910,652,685]" country="China" name="Xizang" pageId="15" pageNumber="422">Xizang</collectingRegion>
) in 1995. The status of MacNeill’s Red Deer is unknown. Poaching and pressure from stock grazing continue to be significant threats.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
